05932nam a22007935i 9780674273726DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222009mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742737267 a10.4159/97806742737262doi  a(DE-B1597)613914  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHD3861 7aPOL0280002bisacsh04a352.5/3097300aGovernment by Contract :bOutsourcing and American Democracy /ced. by Jody Freeman. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (552 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Reframing the Outsourcing Debates -- tI. Recent Developments -- t1. Public-Private Governance: A Historical Introduction -- t2. The Transformation of Government Work: Causes, Consequences, and Distortions -- t3. The Federal Framework for Competing Commercial Work between the Public and Private Sectors -- tII. Cases and Critiques -- t4. Rent-a-Regulator: Design and Innovation in Environmental Decision Making -- t5. Outsourcing Power: Privatizing Military Efforts and the Risks to Accountability, Professionalism, and Democracy -- t6. How Privatization Thinks: The Case of Prisons -- tIII. Responses and Reforms -- t7. Achieving Contracting Goals and Recognizing Public Law Concerns: A Contracting Management Perspective -- t8. Federal Contracting in Context: What Drives It, How to Improve It -- t9. Six Simple Steps to Increase Contractor Accountability -- t10. Privatization and Democracy: Resources in Administrative Law -- t11. Private Delegations, Due Process, and the Duty to Supervise -- t12. Outsourcing and the Duty to Govern -- t13. Public Values/Private Contract -- tNotes -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe dramatic growth of government over the course of the twentieth century since the New Deal prompts concern among libertarians and conservatives and also among those who worry about government’s costs, efficiency, and quality of service. These concerns, combined with rising confidence in private markets, motivate the widespread shift of federal and state government work to private organizations. This shift typically alters only who performs the work, not who pays or is ultimately responsible for it. “Government by contract” now includes military intelligence, environmental monitoring, prison management, and interrogation of terrorism suspects. Outsourcing government work raises questions of accountability. What role should costs, quality, and democratic oversight play in contracting out government work? What tools do citizens and consumers need to evaluate the effectiveness of government contracts? How can the work be structured for optimal performance as well as compliance with public values? Government by Contract explains the phenomenon and scope of government outsourcing and sets an agenda for future research attentive to workforce capacities as well as legal, economic, and political concerns.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aContracting outzUnited States. 0aPrivatizationzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh1 aAman, Alfred C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlum, Mathew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChvotkin, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDickinson, Laura A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDolovich, Sharon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonahue, John D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreeman, Jody, econtributor.4ctb4ht